[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Prototyping in the context of user interface prototyping means building a small version of a system, usually with limited functionality, that can be used to help the user or customer identify the key requirements of a system and demonstrate the feasibility of a design or approach.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "User Interface Prototyping. Prototyping means building a small version of a system, usually with limited functionality, that can be used to help the user or customer identify the key requirements of a system - demonstrate the feasibility of a design or approach",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The prototyping process is often iterative: a prototype is built, evaluated with user and customer feedback, changes are considered to improve the product or design, and another prototype is built until a satisfactory solution is reached.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Often, the prototyping process is iterative: We build a prototype, evaluate it (with user and customer feedback), consider how changes might improve the product or design, and then build another prototype.The iteration ends when we and our customers think we have a satisfactory solution to the problem at hand.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Prototyping is often used to design a good user interface, which is the part of the system with which the user interacts, and it helps bring to the surface issues and assumptions that may not have been clear using other approaches to requirements analysis.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Prototyping is often used to design a good user interface : the part of the system with which the user interacts. ... Since the user interface is, in a sense, a bridge between the application domain and the software development team, prototyping can bring to the surface issues and assumptions that may not have been clear using other approaches to requirements analysis.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

