[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A peer-to-peer (P2P) architecture is defined as one in which each component executes as its own process and acts as both a client of and a server to other peer components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Technically, a peer-to-peer (P2P) architecture is one in which each component executes as its own process and acts as both a client of and a server to other peer components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Each component has an interface that specifies not only the services it provides, but also the services that it requests from other peer components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each component has an interface that specifies not only the services it provides, but also the services that it requests from other peer components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Peers communicate by requesting services from each other, allowing any component to initiate a request to any other peer component.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Peers communicate by requesting services from each other. In this way, P2P communication is like the request/reply communication found in client-server architecture, but any component can initiate a request to any other peer component.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "In P2P architectures, the system's data are distributed among the components, with each component storing data locally and retrieving information from peers when needed.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "What differs among components are the data each component stores locally. Thus, the system's data are distributed among the components; whenever a component needs information not stored locally, it retrieves it from a peer component.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In a publish-subscribe architecture, components interact by broadcasting and reacting to events.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a publish-subscribe architecture, components interact by broadcasting and reacting to events.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A component expresses interest in an event by subscribing to it, and when another component announces (publishes) that the event has taken place, the subscribing components are notified.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A component expresses interest in an event by subscribing to it. Then, when another component announces ( publishes ) that the event has taken place, the subscribing components are notified.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The underlying publish-subscribe infrastructure is responsible for registering event subscriptions and delivering published events to the appropriate components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The underlying publish-subscribe infrastructure is responsible both for registering event subscriptions and for delivering published events to the appropriate components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In implicit invocation, a subscribing component registers one of its procedures with each event of interest, and when the event occurs, the infrastructure invokes all registered procedures.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Implicit invocation is  a  common form of publish-subscribe architecture, in which a subscribing component associates one of its procedures with each event of interest (called registering the procedure). In this case, when the event occurs, the publish-subscribe infrastructure invokes all of the event's registered procedures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Publish-subscribe components know nothing about each other; the publishing component simply announces events and waits for interested components to react, while each subscribing component reacts to event announcements regardless of how they are published.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In contrast to client-server and P2P components, publish-subscribe components know nothing about each other. Instead, the publishing component simply announces events and then waits for interested components to react; each subscribing component simply reacts to event announcements, regardless of how they are published.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

