[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In a Pipe-and-Filter architecture, data is passed sequentially through a series of independent filters via pipes, where each filter transforms the data and passes it along without storing it persistently.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a pipe-and-filter style, illustrated in Figure 5.6, system functionality is achieved by passing input data through a sequence of data-transforming components, called filters, to produce output data. Pipes are connectors that simply transmit data from one filter to the next without modifying the data. Each filter is an independent function that makes no assumptions about other filters that may be applied to the data.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Unlike the other designs, a data item is no longer stored in any location, but rather flows from one filter to another, being transformed along the way.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, a Blackboard repository architecture uses a central data store where shared data is stockpiled, and data-accessing components (knowledge sources) react to the current contents of this store by retrieving, updating, and storing information.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A repository style of architecture consists of two types of components: a central data store and associated data-accessing components. Shared data are stockpiled in the data store, and the data accessors are computational units that store, retrieve, and update the information.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the blackboard type of repository (illustrated in Figure 5.8), the data-accessing components are reactive: they execute in reaction to the current contents of the data store.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the key structural difference is that Pipe-and-Filter architecture transmits data through a pipeline of independent filters without persistent storage, while Blackboard repository architecture centralizes data storage and relies on reactive components that interact through this shared data store.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to the V model, verification and validation activities are linked to specific phases of analysis and design on the left side of the V and corresponding testing phases on the right side.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The V model is a variation of the waterfall model that demonstrates how the testing activities are related to analysis and design (German Ministry of Defense 1992). As shown in Figure 2.4, coding forms the point of the V, with analysis and design on the left, testing and maintenance on the right.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Verification ensures that each phase's outputs conform to the inputs of the next phase, and it is mapped to unit and integration testing which verify the program and system design respectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The V model suggests that unit and integration testing can also be used to verify the program design. That is, during unit and integration testing, the coders and test team members should ensure that all aspects of the program design have been implemented correctly in the code. Similarly, system testing should verify the system design, making sure that all system design aspects are correctly implemented.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Validation is associated with acceptance testing, which is conducted by the customer to validate the requirements and ensure that all requirements have been fully implemented before the system is accepted.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Acceptance testing, which is conducted by the customer rather than the developer, validates the requirements by associating a testing step with each element of the specification; this type of testing checks to see that all requirements have been fully implemented before the system is accepted and paid for.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, verification maps to unit, integration, and system testing phases that check correctness and conformance to design and requirements, while validation maps to acceptance testing that ensures the system meets the customer's needs as specified in the requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The V model suggests that unit and integration testing can also be used to verify the program design... Similarly, system testing should verify the system design... Acceptance testing... validates the requirements...",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A Chief Programmer team might be a poor organizational choice if the majority of the team members are categorized as \"Rational Introverts\" because the chief programmer team structure requires the chief to make decisions quickly and for team members to communicate primarily with the chief rather than with each other, which may not suit introverted team members who prefer to gather information and consider all possible courses of action before deciding.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Clearly, the chief programmer must be good at making decisions quickly, so the chief is likely to be an extrovert. However, if most of the team members are introverts, the chief programmer team may not be the best structure for the project.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The rational introverts also avoid emotional decisions, but they are willing to take time to consider all possible courses of action. Rational introverts are information gatherers; they do not feel comfortable making a decision unless they are convinced that all the facts are at hand.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For projects with a high degree of uncertainty, a more democratic team structure, such as an egoless programming team where all members share responsibility and decisions are made collectively, is recommended as it better accommodates changing requirements and the need for collaboration.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Instead of a single point of responsibility, an egoless approach holds everyone equally responsible. Moreover, the process is separated from the individuals; criticism is made of the product or the result, not the people involved. The egoless team structure is democratic, and all team members vote on a decision, whether it concerns design considerations or testing techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, when there is much uncertainty involved in a project, a more democratic approach may be better.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Object Constraint Language (OCL) supplements a standard UML class diagram by allowing the expression of invariants, preconditions, and post-conditions that augment the model's constraints.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "OCL can augment many of UML's models. For example, it can be used to express invariants, preconditions, and post-conditions in class diagrams",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To enforce that no two publications can share the same call number, an OCL invariant is specified on the Publication class that states for any two publications p1 and p2, if they are not the same publication, then they must have different call numbers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, the constraint literally says that for any two publications, p1 and p2 , returned by allinstances, if p1 and p2 are not the same publication, then they have different call numbers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The specific OCL navigational constructs used to express this invariant include the construct allinstances, which returns all instances of the Publication class, and the symbol :, which applies the attribute or operation of its right operand to all of the objects in its left operand. Additionally, the constructs forall, and, and implies correspond to first-order logic connectives used in the expression.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- Construct allinstances, which returns all instances of the Publication class\n- Symbol which applies the attribute or operation of its right operand to all of the objects in its left operand : ,\n- Constructs forall, and, and implies, which correspond to the first-order connectives described above",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook argues that high-level Petri nets are better suited than state-machine models for representing processes like an emergency room triage because state-machine models might specify only a single order of events, thereby excluding several acceptable behaviors, or they might specify all possible sequences of events, resulting in an overly complex model for a relatively simple problem.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A state-machine model of the emergency room might specify only a single order of events, thereby excluding several acceptable behaviors, or it might specify all possible sequences of events, resulting in an overly complex model for a relatively simple problem.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "In contrast, a Petri net model of the same emergency room nicely avoids both of these problems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A Petri net model of the same emergency room nicely avoids both of these problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "High-level Petri nets extend basic Petri nets by supporting structured tokens and transition actions, which allow modeling control that depends on the value of data and constrain which tokens enable transitions, making them more expressive and suitable for complex scenarios like tracking multiple preliminary events before treatment begins.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Basic Petri nets are fine for modeling how control flows through events or among concurrent entities. But if we want to model control that depends on the value of data (e.g., borrowing a particular book from a collection of books), then we need to use a high-level Petri net notation. A number of extensions to basic Petri nets have been proposed to improve the notation's expressibility, including inhibitor arcs, which enable a transition only if the input place is empty of tokens; priority among transitions; timing constraints; and structured tokens, which have values.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To model our library problem, which tracks information and events for multiple patrons and publications, we need a Petri net notation that supports structured tokens and transition actions (Ghezzi et al. 1991). A transition action constrains which tokens in the input places can enable the transition and specifies the values of the output tokens.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using the Critical Path Method (CPM), a delay in an activity that has zero slack time pushes all subsequent critical path activities forward, forcing them to be late as well if there is no slack.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Notice what happens when an activity on the critical path begins late (i.e., later than its earliest start time). The late start pushes all subsequent critical path activities forward, forcing them to be late, too, if there is no slack.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This cascading delay logically increases the projected staff-days on a resource histogram because the delayed activities and all subsequent activities on the critical path require resources for a longer period than initially planned.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The specific term for the path that contains these zero-slack activities is the critical path.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The longest path has a slack of zero for each of its nodes, because it is the path that determines whether or not the project is on schedule. For this reason, it is called the critical path.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The U.S. government's definition of Return on Investment (ROI) focuses on dollars, looking at reducing operating costs, predicting dollar savings, and calculating the cost of employing new technologies. Government investments are expressed in terms of dollars, such as the cost of introducing new technologies or process improvement initiatives.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The government views ROI in terms of dollars, looking at reducing operating costs, predicting dollar savings, and calculating the cost of employing new technologies. Government investments are also expressed in dollars, such as the cost of introducing new technologies or process improvement initiatives.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, industry views investment in terms of effort rather than cost or dollars. Companies are interested in saving time or using fewer people, and their definition of ROI reflects this focus on decreasing effort. Industry ROI includes factors such as training, schedule, risk, quality, productivity, process, customer, costs, and business.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, industry viewed investment in terms of effort, rather than cost or dollars. That is, companies were interested in saving time or using fewer people, and their definition of return on investment reflected this focus on decreasing effort. Among the companies surveyed, return on investment included such items as training, schedule, risk, quality, productivity, process, customer, costs, business",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The difference arises because dollar savings from reduced schedule, higher quality, and increased productivity are returned to the government rather than the contractor, while contractors seek competitive edge, increased work capacity, and greater profit, making their ROI more effort-based.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Dollar savings from reduced schedule, higher quality, and increased productivity are returned to the government rather than the contractor. On the other hand, contractors are usually looking for a competitive edge and increased work capacity as well as greater profit; thus, the contractor's ROI is more effort- than cost-based.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The payback period is mathematically calculated as the time it takes for the cumulative benefits to equal the initial investment. It is the point where the total benefits minus the total costs equals zero, indicating the investment has been recovered.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The payback period is the time it takes for the cumulative benefits to equal the initial investment, i.e., when total benefits minus total costs equals zero.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The primary development goal of building a throwaway rapid prototype during the requirements elicitation phase is to quickly explore and answer questions about the problem or proposed solution without concern for software quality or reusability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype is software that is developed to learn more about a problem or about a proposed solution, and that is never intended to be part of the delivered software. This approach allows us to write 'quick-and-dirty' software that is poorly structured, inefficient, with no error checking-that, in fact, may be a facade that does not implement any of the desired functionality-but that gets quickly to the heart of questions we have about the problem or about a proposed solution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, building a throwaway rapid prototype during the software architecture design phase focuses on exploring design issues and assessing feasibility, but the prototype is still discarded after learning, and the actual system is built from scratch.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If a prototype is intended only to explore design issues, we may not give its development the same careful attention that we would give to a real system. For this reason, we frequently discard the prototype and build the actual system from scratch, rather than try to salvage parts from the prototype. In these cases, the throw-away prototype is meant to be discarded; its development is intended only to assess the feasibility or particular characteristics in a proposed design.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, during requirements elicitation, the throwaway prototype is primarily a tool for understanding and clarifying requirements, while during software architecture design, it is primarily a tool for exploring and validating design decisions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype is software that is developed to learn more about a problem or about a proposed solution... Once our questions are answered, we throw away the prototype software and start engineering the software that will be delivered.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If a prototype is intended only to explore design issues... the throw-away prototype is meant to be discarded; its development is intended only to assess the feasibility or particular characteristics in a proposed design.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The representation of conditions and states in a Parnas Table for calculating a library due date is structured as a tabular format where column and row headers are predicates specifying cases, and the internal table entries store the possible function results.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A Normal Table, which is a type of Parnas table. The column and row headers are predicates used to specify cases, and the internal table entries store the possible function results.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Each internal table entry represents a distinct case in the function's definition, covering all possible combinations of conditions that affect the calculation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Notice how the column and row headers are structured to cover all possible combinations of conditions that can affect the calculation of a loaned item's due date.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the representation of pre-conditions and post-conditions in a formal Z specification schema for a \"Return\" operation is expressed through logical expressions and function updates that specify the state changes before and after the operation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Operation Return is more complicated. It takes as input the library Item being returned, the Patron who borrowed the Item, and the Date of the return. The post-conditions remove the returned item from variables Borrowers and DueDates; these updates use Z symbol y, 'domain subtraction,' to return a submapping of their pre-operation values, excluding any element whose domain value is the Item being returned.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The post-conditions specify updates to variables using algebraic symbols to override or map domain values, reflecting precise state changes rather than case-based function results.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "These updates use symbol å, which 'maps' a domain value 'to' a range value, and symbol ± which 'overrides' a function mapping, usually with a new 'maps-to' element.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, structurally, Parnas Tables organize conditions and states in a case-based tabular format focusing on function results per condition combination, while Z specification schemas use logical and algebraic expressions to define precise pre-conditions and post-conditions that describe state transformations.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A functional specification expressed using Parnas tables is best decomposed into a single function per output variable. For every input event and for every condition on entities or other variables, each function specifies the value of its corresponding output variable.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Operation Return is more complicated. It takes as input the library Item being returned, the Patron who borrowed the Item, and the Date of the return. The post-conditions remove the returned item from variables Borrowers and DueDates; these updates use Z symbol y, 'domain subtraction,' to return a submapping of their pre-operation values, excluding any element whose domain value is the Item being returned.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The \"hot standby\" redundancy fault-recovery tactic failed during the Ariane-5 maiden flight because software failures among replicated components in hot standby mode are rarely independent, unlike hardware failures.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "hardware failures are very different from software failures. Hardware failures are independent: if one unit fails, the standby unit is usually unaffected and can take over as the active unit. By contrast, software faults tend to be logical errors, so all copies of a software component have the same set of faults. Moreover, even if the software is not the underlying cause of a failure, replicated software components are likely to exhibit the same bad behavior in response to bad input. For these reasons, the hot standby redundancy in Ariane-5 is likely to recover only from hardware failures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook explains that hardware failures are independent, meaning if one hardware unit fails, the standby unit remains unaffected and can take over. However, software failures are typically logical errors that affect all copies of the software component simultaneously, especially when processing the same input, leading to simultaneous failure of both active and standby software components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Hardware failures are independent: if one unit fails, the standby unit is usually unaffected and can take over as the active unit. By contrast, software faults tend to be logical errors, so all copies of a software component have the same set of faults. Moreover, even if the software is not the underlying cause of a failure, replicated software components are likely to exhibit the same bad behavior in response to bad input.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In the case of Ariane-5, both inertial reference systems (SRIs) suffered the same overflow error simultaneously, demonstrating that the hot standby redundancy could not recover from this software failure.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This was the situation with the failed inertial reference systems (SRIs) on the Ariane-5: both units suffered the same overflow error, simultaneously.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A 'pure' layered architecture, such as the OSI model, utilizes the tactic of reducing coupling by restricting each software unit in a given layer to access only the units in the same layer and the services offered by the interface to the layer immediately below it.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a 'pure' layered system, a software unit in a given layer can access only the other units in the same layer and services offered by the interface to the layer immediately below it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This use of explicit interfaces between layers ensures that changes in one layer affect at most only the two adjacent layers, minimizing the impact on indirectly affected software units.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, because a layer can interact only with its neighboring layers, layer modification is relatively easy; such changes should affect at most only the two adjacent layers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The OSI model exemplifies this by providing a clear separation of concerns where each layer raises the level of abstraction and hides the implementation details of the services it provides to the next layer, thus supporting maintainability and portability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the OSI example, each layer raises the level of abstraction of the communication services that are available to the next layer, and hides all of the details about how those services are implemented.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The transition from Stage 1 (Application Composition) to Stage 3 (Postarchitecture) in the COCOMO II model changes the metrics used to measure system size from application points to function points or source lines of code (SLOC).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Size, Stage 1: Application Composition = Application points. Size, Stage 3: Postarchitecture = FP and language or source lines of code (SLOC).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At stage 1, application points supply the size measure. ... By stage 3, the postarchitecture stage, development has begun, and far more information is known. In this stage, sizing can be done in terms of function points or lines of code",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Regarding cost drivers, Stage 1 has no product, platform, personnel, or project cost drivers explicitly applied, while Stage 3 includes a wide range of cost drivers such as reliability, database size, documentation needs, required reuse, product complexity, execution time constraints, main storage constraints, virtual machine volatility, analyst capability, applications experience, programmer capability, programmer experience, language and tool experience, personnel continuity, use of software tools, required development schedule, and multisite development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Product cost drivers, Stage 1: Application Composition = None. Product cost drivers, Stage 3: Postarchitecture = Reliability, database size, documentation needs, required reuse,and product complexity. Platform cost drivers, Stage 1: Application Composition = None. Platform cost drivers, Stage 3: Postarchitecture = Execution time constraints, main storage constraints,and virtual machine volatility. Personnel cost drivers, Stage 1: Application Composition = None. Personnel cost drivers, Stage 3: Postarchitecture = Analyst capability, applications experience,programmer capability,programmer experience, language and tool experience,and personnel continuity. Project cost drivers, Stage 1: Application Composition = None. Project cost drivers, Stage 3: Postarchitecture = Use of software tools, required development schedule,and multisite development",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, as the project progresses from Stage 1 to Stage 3, the size metrics evolve from high-level application points to more detailed function points or lines of code, and the cost drivers become more comprehensive and detailed, reflecting the increased knowledge and complexity of the project.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By stage 3, the postarchitecture stage, development has begun, and far more information is known. In this stage, sizing can be done in terms of function points or lines of code, and many cost factors can be estimated with some degree of comfort.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Developers can use fit criteria to transform a subjective quality requirement like Usability into an objectively testable specification by quantifying the extent to which the requirement must be met.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Robertson and Robertson (1999) point out that testability (which they call 'measurability') can be addressed when requirements are being elicited. The idea is to quantify the extent to which each requirement must be met. These fit criteria form objective standards for judging whether a proposed solution satisfies the requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, a subjective requirement such as 'Water quality information must be accessible immediately' can be restated more precisely as 'Water quality records must be retrieved within 5 seconds of a request,' which can then be tested objectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, a customer may state a quality requirement this way: Water quality information must be accessible immediately. How do you test that your product meets this requirement? The customer probably has a clear idea about what 'immediately' means, and that notion must be captured in the requirement. We can restate more precisely what we mean by 'immediately': Water quality records must be retrieved within 5 seconds of a request. This second formulation of the requirement can be tested objectively: a series of requests is made, and we check that the system supplies the appropriate record within 5 seconds of each request.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Similarly, for usability, fit criteria can include measurable goals such as '75% of users shall judge the new system to be as usable as the existing system' or 'After training, 90% of users shall be able to process a new account within 5 minutes,' which provide objective standards for evaluation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In these cases, developers use focus groups or metrics to evaluate fit criteria: - 75% of users shall judge the new system to be as usable as the existing system. - After training, 90% of users shall be able to process a new account within 5 minutes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This approach aligns with McCall's quality model, where external quality factors like Usability are linked to internal criteria such as Operability and Training, allowing developers to measure and improve these internal aspects to meet the usability goals.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Users judge software to be of high quality if it does what they want in a way that is easy to learn and easy to use. ... McCall associated each right-hand criterion with a measurement to indicate the degree to which an element of quality was addressed (McCall, Richards, and Walters 1977).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "FIGURE 1.5 McCall's quality model.",
                "img_id": "image_0_0"
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The initial risk exposure is calculated by multiplying the risk probability by the risk impact.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can quantify the effects of the risks we identify by multiplying the risk impact by the risk probability, to yield the risk exposure.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Given a risk probability of 0.25 and a potential loss impact of $500,000, the initial risk exposure is 0.25 × $500,000 = $125,000.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To determine the risk reduction leverage, the project manager must calculate the difference in risk exposure before and after the risk reduction, then divide that difference by the cost of reducing the risk.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To aid decision making about risk reduction, we must take into account the cost of reducing the risk. We call risk leverage the difference in risk exposure divided by the cost of reducing the risk.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Mathematically, risk reduction leverage = (Risk exposure before reduction - Risk exposure after reduction) / Cost of risk reduction.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "risk reduction leverage is If the leverage value is not high enough to justify the action, then we can look for other less costly or more effective reduction techniques. / 1 cost of risk reduction 2 1 Risk exposure before reduction -risk exposure after reduction 2",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The project manager must estimate the new risk exposure after applying the mitigation strategy to complete this calculation.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A Message Sequence Chart (MSC) visually depicts the passage of time by using vertical lines representing participating entities, with time progressing from top to bottom along these lines. Each horizontal line between two vertical lines represents an event or interaction, usually a message passed from one entity to another, showing the sequence of events over time.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each vertical line represents a participating entity, and a message is depicted as an arrow from the sending entity to the receiving entity; time progresses from the top to the bottom of the trace, so if one event appears above another event, then the upper event occurs before the lower event.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "MSCs also have facilities for creating and destroying entities, specifying actions and timers, and composing traces.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Message Sequence Charts (ITU 1996) are an enhanced event-trace notation, with facilities for creating and destroying entities, specifying actions and timers, and composing traces.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, a UML Statechart diagram depicts the local variables and internal activities of a single entity by showing how a class's instances change state and how their attributes change value as the objects interact with each other. It focuses on the dynamic behavior of the objects of a class, including state hierarchy, concurrency, and intermachine communication.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A UML statechart diagram depicts the dynamic behavior of the objects in a UML class. A UML class diagram gives a static, big-picture view of a problem, in terms of the entities involved and their relationships; it says nothing about how the entities behave, or how their behaviors change in response to input events. A statechart diagram shows how a class's instances should change state and how their attributes should change value as the objects interact with each other.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "UML statechart diagrams have a rich syntax, much of it borrowed from Harel's original conception of statecharts (Harel 1987), including state hierarchy, concurrency, and intermachine communication.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Thus, MSCs emphasize the temporal sequence and interaction between multiple entities, while UML Statechart diagrams emphasize the internal state changes and activities within a single entity.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to Abdel-Hamid's system dynamics model of software development, increasing the staff size to alleviate schedule pressure inadvertently impacts the average nominal potential productivity and communication overhead.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The figure shows us that average nominal potential productivity is affected by three things: the productivity of the experienced staff, the fraction of experienced staff, and the productivity of the new staff. At the same time, new staff must learn about the project; as more of the project is completed, the more the new staff must learn before they can become productive members of the team.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Similarly, the larger the staff (reflected in staff size), the more time is devoted to communication among project members (communication overhead).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Increasing staff size to reduce schedule pressure increases communication overhead because the number of communication pairs grows as n(n-1)/2, which requires more time for coordination among team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We know that if n people are assigned to a project, then there are n ( n -1)/2 potential pairs of people who must communicate and coordinate with one another.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "At the same time, adding new staff lowers the average nominal potential productivity because new staff are less productive initially and require time to learn about the project before becoming productive.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The figure shows us that average nominal potential productivity is affected by three things: the productivity of the experienced staff, the fraction of experienced staff, and the productivity of the new staff. At the same time, new staff must learn about the project; as more of the project is completed, the more the new staff must learn before they can become productive members of the team.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A company justifies the initial higher development costs of creating a core asset base for a software product line by expecting that these costs will be more than offset by the savings accrued from deriving family members from the product line.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "more than offset by the savings we expect to accrue from deriving family members from the product line.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Strategically, the company plans upfront to manufacture and market several related products that share assets and resources, which reduces the cost and effort to develop the family of products compared to developing each product individually.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The corporate strategy for designing and developing the related products is based on the reuse of elements of a common product line . The company plans upfront to manufacture and market several related products. Part of the planning process involves deciding how those products will share assets and resources. ... As a result, the cost and effort to develop the family of products is far less than the sum of the costs to develop the products individually.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The 'scoping' of product commonality affects the eventual return on investment because if the scope is too narrow (insisting on high commonality like 80% code reuse), some profitable products outside the scope may be excluded, while if the scope is too broad, the degree of commonality among derived products decreases, reducing the savings achievable.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Product-line scoping is a challenging problem. If we strive for some notion of optimal commonality among the products (e.g.,by insisting on reusing 80 percent of the code), we may exclude some interesting and profitable products that lie outside of the scope. On the other hand, if we try to include any product that looks related, we reduce the degree of commonality among the derived products, and consequently the amount of savings that can be achieved.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, a successful product line lies somewhere in the middle of these extremes, with a core architecture that strongly supports the more promising products, ensuring that each derived product incorporates a significant fraction of software units from the core asset base to achieve desired productivity improvements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A successful product line lies somewhere in the middle of these two extremes, with a core architecture that strongly supports the more promising products that we want to build. In the end, a product line's success depends on both its inherent variability and the degree of overlap between its core asset base and the derived products. To obtain desired productivity-improvement numbers, each derived product's architecture must start with the product-line architecture, incorporating a significant fraction of its software units from the product line's core asset base.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The \"Transformed Specification\" in the operational specification process model represents a formal, precise transformation of a specification into a deliverable system through a series of automated steps such as changing data representations, selecting algorithms, optimizing, and compiling.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Balzer's transformational model tries to reduce the opportunity for error by eliminating several major development steps. Using automated support, the transformational process applies a series of transformations to change a specification into a deliverable system (Balzer 1981a). Sample transformations can include - changing the data representations - selecting algorithms - optimizing - compiling",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This process requires a formal specification expressed precisely so that the transformations can operate on it, and the sequence of transformations and decisions are kept as a formal development record.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because many paths can be taken from the specification to the delivered system, the sequence of transformations and the decisions they reflect are kept as a formal development record. The transformational approach holds great promise. However, a major impediment to its use is the need for a formal specification expressed precisely so the transformations can operate on it",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the transition between a throwaway prototype and an evolutionary prototype during requirements engineering involves building a prototype to elicit user feedback and refine requirements, especially when customers are uncertain or have only a wish list of needs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When trying to determine requirements, we may find that our customers are uncertain of exactly what they want or need. Elicitation may yield only a 'wish list' of what the customers would like to see, with few details or without being clear as to whether the list is complete. ... one way that we can elicit details is to build a prototype of the proposed system and to solicit feedback from potential users about what aspects they would like to see improved, which features are not so useful, or what functionality is missing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the throwaway prototype is used to explore and clarify requirements, while the evolutionary prototype is incrementally refined based on user feedback to evolve into the final system, merging functionality and design early on.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "an operational specification allows the functionality and the design to be merged. Figure 2.6 illustrates how an operational specification works. Notice that the operational specification is similar to prototyping; the process enables user and developer to examine requirements early on.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In summary, the transformed specification in the operational specification model is a formal, automated transformation from specification to system, whereas the transition from throwaway to evolutionary prototype is an iterative, user-driven refinement of requirements and design.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Data-flow diagrams (DFDs) provide an intuitive model of a proposed system's high-level functionality and data dependencies among various processes, which helps domain experts understand the system easily.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the strengths of data-flow diagrams is that they provide an intuitive model of a proposed system's high-level functionality and of the data dependencies among the various processes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In Stage 1 of the COCOMO II estimation model, Application Points are used to estimate size based on high-level effort generators such as the number of screens, reports, and third-generation language components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At stage 1, projects usually build prototypes to resolve high-risk issues involving user interfaces, software and system interaction, performance, or technological maturity. Here, little is known about the likely size of the final product under consideration, so COCOMO II estimates size in what its creators call application points. As we shall see, this technique captures size in terms of highlevel effort generators, such as the number of screens and reports, and the number of third-generation language components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The data stores and actors identified in the DFD would influence the complexity weights used to calculate Application Points by representing key elements that contribute to the system's high-level functionality and data interactions, which are factors in determining the number and complexity of screens, reports, and components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the strengths of data-flow diagrams is that they provide an intuitive model of a proposed system's high-level functionality and of the data dependencies among the various processes.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At stage 1, projects usually build prototypes to resolve high-risk issues involving user interfaces, software and system interaction, performance, or technological maturity. Here, little is known about the likely size of the final product under consideration, so COCOMO II estimates size in what its creators call application points. As we shall see, this technique captures size in terms of highlevel effort generators, such as the number of screens and reports, and the number of third-generation language components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, DFDs can be ambiguous in terms of the exact data flows and processes, so the interpretation of data stores and actors must be done carefully to accurately reflect the system's complexity in the Application Points calculation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In particular, there are multiple ways of interpreting a DFD process that has multiple input flows (e.g., process Borrow ): are all inputs needed to compute the function, is only one of the inputs needed, or is some subset of the inputs needed? Similarly, there are multiple ways of interpreting a DFD process that has multiple output flows: are all outputs generated every time the process executes, is only one of the outputs generated, or is some subset generated? It is also not obvious that two data flows with the same annotation represent the same values: are the Items Returned that flow from Return to Loan Records the same as the Items Returned that flow from Return to Process Fines ? For these reasons, DFDs are best used by users who are familiar with the application domain being modeled, and as early models of a problem, when details are less important.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To achieve the external quality factor of Flexibility by minimizing the number of indirectly affected software units when a change occurs, specific modifiability tactics should be applied to the system's interfaces and coupling.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By contrast, tactics for minimizing the impact on indirectly affected software units focus on reducing dependencies among software units.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The specific modifiability tactics to apply are",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Lowering coupling among software units to reduce the likelihood that a change to one unit will ripple to other units.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Coupling: As we discuss in detail in Chapter 6,the level of coupling among software units is the degree to which the units depend on each other. By lowering coupling, we reduce the likelihood that a change to one unit will ripple to other units.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Ensuring that software units interact only through their interfaces, which reveal the unit's public requisites and responsibilities while hiding private design decisions, so that changes do not spread beyond the unit's boundary unless its interface changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Interfaces: A software unit's interface reveals the unit's public requisites and responsibilities, and hides the unit's private design decisions. If a unit interacts with other units only through their interfaces (e.g., calling public access methods), then changes to one unit will not spread beyond the unit's boundary unless its interface changes (e.g., if method signatures, preconditions, or postconditions change).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Providing new data or services through new interfaces without changing existing interfaces, so dependencies on existing interfaces remain unaffected by changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Multiple interfaces: A unit modified to provide new data or services can offer them using a new interface to the unit without changing any of the unit's existing interfaces. This way, dependencies on the existing interfaces are unaffected by the change.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Establishing specific fit criteria for subjective quality requirements like usability during the requirements phase makes the requirement more precise and objectively testable.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can restate more precisely what we mean by 'immediately': Water quality records must be retrieved within 5 seconds of a request. This second formulation of the requirement can be tested objectively",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "What about more subjective quality requirements, like usability or maintainability? In these cases, developers use focus groups or metrics to evaluate fit criteria: - 75% of users shall judge the new system to be as usable as the existing system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "By defining such measurable fit criteria, the risk parameters such as risk impact and risk probability become easier to quantify because the requirement's success or failure can be objectively evaluated rather than being vague or uncertain.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is relatively easy to determine fit criteria for quality requirements that are naturally quantitative (e.g., performance, size, precision, accuracy, time to delivery). What about more subjective quality requirements, like usability or maintainability? In these cases, developers use focus groups or metrics to evaluate fit criteria",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can quantify the effects of the risks we identify by multiplying the risk impact by the risk probability, to yield the risk exposure.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, the establishment of specific fit criteria during the requirements phase reduces uncertainty in risk assessment, allowing for more accurate calculation of risk exposure and more effective risk control measures during project planning.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The key is to determine, with the customer, just how to demonstrate that a delivered system meets its requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For each risk, we must determine what we can do to minimize or avoid the impact of the event. Risk control involves a set of actions taken to reduce or eliminate a risk.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A highly hierarchical Chief Programmer team structure theoretically faces fewer communication bottlenecks than a loosely structured, egoless team because it minimizes the amount of communication needed during the project by centralizing all decision-making with the chief programmer.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By placing all responsibility for all decisions with the chief programmer, the team structure minimizes the amount of communication needed during the project. Each team member must communicate often with the chief, but not necessarily with other team members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This structure establishes only paths of communication between each team member and the chief, avoiding the complexity of multiple communication paths among team members, which reduces communication bottlenecks.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, if the team consists of programmers plus the chief, the team can establish only paths of communication (one path for each team member's interaction with the chief) out of a potential paths.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, an egoless team is democratic with all members equally responsible and voting on decisions, which can increase communication overhead and potential bottlenecks.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The egoless team structure is democratic, and all team members vote on a decision, whether it concerns design considerations or testing techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When developing a system specified with a tightly coupled algebraic specification notation like SDL Data, where processes are highly coupled and need synchronization, having a clear, centralized decision-making structure helps manage the complexity and communication more efficiently.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Signal routes pass messages synchronously, so messages sent between processes in the same block are received instantaneously. In fact, this difference in communication mechanisms is a factor when deciding how to decompose behavior: processes that need to synchronize with one another and that are highly coupled should reside in the same block.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A single-element cut-set (e.g., {A1}) derived from a fault-tree analysis strictly represents a minimal event combination that could lead to the top failure in the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, if any member of the cut-set is a singleton event set, {A i }, then the top failure could be caused by a single event, A i .",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "From the internal developer view, this single event {A1} corresponds to a fault, which is an encoding of an error made by a human during software development or design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A fault occurs when a human makes a mistake, called an error, in performing some software activity.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "From the system's observable behavior perspective, the occurrence of this fault leads to a failure, which is a departure from the system's required behavior.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A failure is a departure from the system's required behavior.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, the single-element cut-set represents a fault (internal developer view) that, when it occurs, causes a failure (observable system behavior).",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Lai's process transition diagram models a process statically by showing relationships among roles, activities, and artifacts, focusing on elements such as activities, sequences, process models, and resources.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In particular, the elements of a process are viewed in terms of seven types: 1. Activity: Something that will happen in a process. ... 2. Sequence: The order of activities. ... 3. Process model: A view of interest about the system. ... 4. Resource: A necessary item, tool, or person.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, a high-level Petri net model, such as the one used for the library problem, represents conditions and states as places that store tokens representing different data types, and transitions that fire when enabled by the presence of tokens in input places, thereby modeling concurrent activities and their interactions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Petri nets (Peterson 1977) are a form of state-transition notation that is used to model concurrent activities and their interactions. ... The circles in the net are places that represent activities or conditions, and the bars represent transitions. ... The places are populated with tokens, which act as enabling conditions for the transitions. When a transition fires, it removes tokens from each of its input places and inserts tokens into each of its output places.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each place stores tokens of a different data type. Avail stores a token for every library item that is not currently out on loan. ... The net starts with an initial marking of item tuples in Avail and (patron, 0) tuples in Fines. As library users trigger input transitions Pay, Initiate Loan, and Initiate Return, new tokens are introduced to the system, which enable the library transitions, which in turn fire and update the Fines tokens and the Avail and OnLoan tokens, and so on.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Structurally, Lai's diagrams emphasize static relationships and sequences among process elements, while Petri nets emphasize dynamic state changes through token flow and transition firing, representing enabling conditions explicitly via tokens in places.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A static model depicts the process, showing that the inputs are transformed to outputs. A dynamic model enacts the process, so the user can see how intermediate and final products are transformed over time.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Petri nets ... are a form of state-transition notation that is used to model concurrent activities and their interactions. ... The places are populated with tokens, which act as enabling conditions for the transitions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Modeling the complete system's dynamic behavior using Message Sequence Charts (MSCs) in a pure publish-subscribe architectural style with implicit invocation is inherently difficult because the behavior of a publishing component depends on which subscribing components are monitoring its events, making it impossible to test the component in isolation and infer its correctness in an integrated system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Publish-subscribe systems are difficult to test, because the behavior of a publishing component will depend on which subscribing components are monitoring its events. Thus, we cannot test the component in isolation and infer its correctness in an integrated system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, MSCs are usually used only to describe key scenarios rather than to specify entire problems because of the trace-explosion problem, which is exacerbated in publish-subscribe systems due to the many possible interactions between publishers and multiple subscribers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Message Sequence Charts are usually used only to describe key scenarios rather than to specify entire problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, attempting to model the complete dynamic behavior of a publish-subscribe system with MSCs can be misleading because the implicit invocation style leads to complex, many-to-many interactions that are difficult to capture fully and accurately in MSCs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If the resulting architecture is expressed as a collection of models, we must document how the models relate to one another. If one model simply shows the decomposition of an element from a more abstract model, then this relationship is straightforward. If, instead, two models show different views of the system, and if there is no obvious mapping between the two views' software units, then documenting the views' correspondence is all the more important.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Publish-subscribe systems are difficult to test, because the behavior of a publishing component will depend on which subscribing components are monitoring its events. Thus, we cannot test the component in isolation and infer its correctness in an integrated system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In Extreme Programming (XP), future, unanticipated requirements are not planned or designed for; the system is built only to the requirements defined at the time, with no anticipation of possible future needs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Extreme programming (XP) takes agile requirements processes to the extreme, in that the system is built to the requirements that happen to be defined at the time, with no planning or designing for possible future requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "XP emphasizes simplicity by addressing only current needs and avoids anticipating future needs to prevent unnecessary functionality.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Simple design: Design is kept simple by addressing only current needs.This approach reflects the philosophy that anticipating future needs can lead to unnecessary functionality.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the strategic approach used when scoping and designing a core asset base for a Software Product Line architecture involves planning and designing for future, unanticipated requirements to enable reuse and adaptability across multiple products.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The software industry's definition of Return on Investment (ROI) primarily focuses on effort reduction and time savings, emphasizing benefits such as training, schedule, risk, quality, productivity, process, customer satisfaction, and costs related to meeting predictions and staying within budget.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, industry viewed investment in terms of effort, rather than cost or dollars. That is, companies were interested in saving time or using fewer people, and their definition of return on investment reflected this focus on decreasing effort. Among the companies surveyed, return on investment included such items as training, schedule, risk, quality, productivity, process, customer, costs, business. The cost issues included in the definition involve meeting cost predictions, improving cost performance, and staying within budget, rather than reducing operating costs or streamlining the project or organization.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the mathematical calculation of a design's payback period in a formal cost-benefit analysis is a quantitative financial measure that calculates the length of time before accumulated benefits recover the costs of implementation, with an ROI ratio indicating whether benefits outweigh costs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Another useful measure is the payback period : the length of time before accumulated benefits recover the costs of implementation. In our example, the payback period for restructuring the sorted-index module (design 2) is $300,000/$280,000 = 1.07 of a year = approximately 13 months. Computing Return on Investment (ROI). The return on investment of making one of these design changes is the ratio of the benefits gained from making the change to the cost of its implementation: These costs are estimated using the techniques described in Chapter 3. In general, an ROI of 1 or greater means that the design's benefits outweigh its costs. The higher the ROI value, the more effective the design.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, while the software industry's ROI definition is effort- and time-based and often qualitative, focusing on competitive advantage and productivity improvements, the formal cost-benefit analysis uses a precise financial calculation to evaluate the economic effectiveness of design changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Dollar savings from reduced schedule, higher quality, and increased productivity are returned to the government rather than the contractor. On the other hand, contractors are usually looking for a competitive edge and increased work capacity as well as greater profit; thus, the contractor's ROI is more effort- than cost-based.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Computing Return on Investment (ROI). The return on investment of making one of these design changes is the ratio of the benefits gained from making the change to the cost of its implementation: These costs are estimated using the techniques described in Chapter 3. In general, an ROI of 1 or greater means that the design's benefits outweigh its costs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    }
]
